column120: These surveys come from an extremely out of touch perspective. For starters, when you are asking about leadership, there needs to be a distinction between corporate leadership and local leadership. Do I trust my local leadership team, absolutely, do I trust the corporate leadership team, not as much. Generalized questions about leadership teams when you work for a tiered organization lead to ambiguous answers.  Also, It seems corporate leaders are a little out of touch with what drives employee participation. Most people at lower levels do not live and breath mission statements. We base our decisions to continue working for a company on factors like, am I fairly compensated for my time, does my direct manager support me when I have a problem, am I able to take sick days when necessary, and do I have a clear understanding of what my job entails.  People don't need happy mantras and fancy attribute acronyms to be good employees. They need good bosses, competent co-workers, and reasonable compensation.

column11: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/84.0.4147.89 Safari/537.36
column95: The core leaders need to understand what happens in the field- not just one trip once or twice a year and talking only to the top management. Ever heard of the fox guarding the hen house? Field management is very self serving and manipulates SOP to their needs/wants at the time. Knee jerk reacting instead of proper research. Badgering of hard workers who bring issues to light, and no accountability for those lacking.  I feel we have an amazing mission and great core values, but they fall flat at my location. It isn't enough. We are constantly pushed to the extreme and taken advantage of- moral is at an all time low and you are slowly losing DECADES of experience and DEDICATED employees. It is a shame the flagship location has been run into the ground and is now being turned into a mini SCI.  I would hope others are just as honest as me on this survey. I have to believe not every location is this way, otherwise the core values and missions I believe about Northstar aren't true. I come to work daily despite the toxic environment and do my best to serve our families, because I believe in what we do and that is why I still cling to a morsel of hope it will get better.

column95: Higher base pay is a constant issue among employee's that is ever present on a weekly basis. We live in an uncertain, turbulent world that beacons constant reminders that members of this organization are the  epitome of front-line workers, however some feel their pay is not reflective of their worth to the company or even to the location they work at. 30 or 40 cent raises every year are not consistent with the ever increasing cost of living prices in this world, and management having to convince employees that they're being paid a fair wage for everything that is asked of them, especially during this Covd-19 pandemic, is becoming more and more difficult to justify. The end result ultimately  leads to unnecessary turnover when once happy employee's become disgruntled over pay... Having to hire people who are desperate for *any* pay regardless of the job rarely fosters the best applicants, and as such, the company gets what they pay for. This results in an endless cycle of hiring, training, distrust, frustration, turnover, hiring, training... Etc. etc.

column95: have signature pads for contracts instead of plain docusign when in person.  When a person buys a preneed for cremation if the contract is signed by the person it acts as a Cremation authorization form.  Per Texas law.   However when it is signed by docusign it cannot be since it does not have the wet signature of the person.   In this day and time where people don't have close legal next of kin that signed document will release company of liability and make it easier to cremate the decease.

column120: I come from Neptune Society, and I will NEVER go back.  The culture here is completely the opposite of the culture there.  The management team always had an "us vs. them" philosophy, with the executive management team always battling the regionals, and sales managers.  There was NO trust.  The executive team did everything to prove they didn't deserve to be trusted.  Contrast that with NSMG, and Smart Cremation.  I have no doubt that we are all alligned on the same mission.  My successes are the team's successes.  Everyone has each other's backs.  I trust that the executive team is looking out for me, and they can trust that I will do my best every day.  Period.  I love this company.  I think I can do this job until I'm 80.   Let's see.

column95: Employees should be empowered to make decisions to best serve families and do the right thing ethically. In my experience, management will not stand behind decisions that best serve families grieving the loss of a loved one, even when they are made with both ethics and the company in mind. This results in employees feeling they must get permission from management for any situation that is slightly out of the ordinary. This undermines employees ability to confidently serve families and means management is overwhelmed with small matters that employees could handle, given a certain amount of autonomy to do so. It also results in families frustrated that the matter cannot be resolved in a timely matter, as management is often unavailable, in meetings, etc. It would serve families and their perception of the company better if employees were empowered to make things right/do the right thing for the family with confidence and compassion.
column96: I love serving families in my capacity as funeral director.  Any day were departments work together for the best possible experience for a family, or a service is really and truly personalized and I have a change to go above and beyond for a family is a "Best Day". I get to be myself and use what makes me unique as a person to craft the most memorable and special experience for a family. On days like these I feel fulfilled in my role and as a person, and confident I have provided the best possible service to the family.

column120: In general, funeral directors are consistently held accountable for responsibilities of others. If another department makes a mistake or drops the ball, we are to blame. This creates a lack of trust and resentment between departments. Departments should be held accountable for their own responsibilities. This would foster trust between departments and a sense of teamwork throughout the company. It would also make each department's workload more manageable if they were able to focus on their responsibilities and trust that other departments would follow through as well. If funeral directors are held accountable for the work of every department and must babysit them in order to avoid reprimand, funeral directors should facilitate all aspects of funeral service instead of relying on other departments, and more funeral directors should be hired to handle increased workload.  Within my team of funeral directors, I feel supported, mentored, and that we hold ourselves and each other accountable. I answered for my Northstar location team as a whole. I do not feel supported or mentored by management, admin, or our family service advisors/sales team. It does not seem that these groups are held accountable or always seek to do what is best for the families we serve.   I wish all departments were better attuned to the realities families face after the loss of a loved one. I feel that our mission statement/purpose and the core values we talk about are not realized in the way we do business or approach mistakes or our client families.

column95: We often, but not always, make a point to test new systems and processes among the front line people before rolling them out. There is room for improvement here, though, in getting genuine feedback as we are putting together systems and processes that affect the locations' front line employees. While we are pretty good about communicating a change that is coming, we can be better about letting some front-line people try them out before going live. Especially now, stability is important for our Arrangers, Advisors and Admin. When the world around us is changing frequently, it's important that internal changes be scrutinized in order to roll them out as seamless as possible.
column96: I often have ideas that would not be considered at other companies. I have never had an instance of being shut down with one of these at NSMG. I am confident in presenting my ideas to my leadership, knowing that they highly value an entrepreneurial spirit among their location leadership. My best days are the ones where I am challenged on an idea but ultimately trusted to implement and see if it works.

column95: I highly recommend that we have a more streamlined onboarding system in place.  All application checked off on the Access form should be readily available to the new hire.  Every new hire I have brought on board has had many applications not available and I have had to make several requests to add the applications once we know they are missing.  Often times the hold up is days before we get the application on the PC of the advisor.  This slows down their progress.  The second recommendation would be to add additional people to the IT team.  We are on the West coast and far too often we do not have responses to our tickets for several days.  Many times we have to send tickets numerous times to get a resolution.  The team is eager to help, yet they are overwhelmed.  Please hire at least two more qualified IT people to help NorthStar grow.  Thank you for all that you do!
column96: I have many best days.  NorthStar is a very supportive company.  Our upper management live and breathe our mission.  They lead by example and treat each one of us with the care they expect us to deliver to our clients (internal and external).  With that said, my best day starts with a collaboration meeting with my coworkers in the morning huddle.  During the day we serve families and help them through the worst days of their lives or help them pre-arrange for their final plans.  I set challenges up for my team to exceed their weekly expectations.  We celebrate successes and grow.  I am proud to be part of the NorthStar Family.  My anniversary is around the corner.  Thank you for inviting me to join the family.

column120: 1. micro managing is overdone and so is the phone critiquing-it has a negative impact on employees and makes you not want to come back to work 2. a company goal is great to work towards -  3. counselors working as teams should continue, it's a better incentive for the sales team-  working on their own, is not.   4. a sales incentive of bonus money should be offered to the team I have been with the company for a while now and I can honestly say that my co-workers are like family to me. column95: The single biggest morale "Buster" is answering the phones and feeling like we are being judged by the company as a good or bad employee if we some how do not get all the information out the way the company wants it. Although we are aware that we "sell the company" we were not hired to make a sale.  The organization should have a Trained Sales associate answering All calls in Funeral Homes. These individuals would work part time shifts but cover the 40 work week.  Paid a salary  and bonus on sales both PN and AN(They would not write business).    being expected to be a polished sales person for the company. WThese individuals would 1. Eliminate any "missed" opportunities. 2. help busy associates and admin from answering calls not directly needing their attention, making them more efficient and less distracted. 3. It would insure the NorthStar Promise is effectively presented for a great first impression. 4. The field sales team will benefit by increased appts, and can focus on meeting their families,outside sales  and other self generated leads. 5. It will allow Funeral directors the time to prepare, and focus on the families they serve, ensuring the best customer service experience.6. This person would also make the follow up calls to families we served in the past, which could lead to increased sales. 7. The assoc would also be avilable for 2up or PN in house, in the event an Advisor could not make it. So the greatest positive impact would increase sales! and lift morale.

column95: Making the sales team abide by policy & procedure. As an admin its my sole purpose to do everything "by the book", yet on a daily basis we are bending rules, policies & procedures to adhere to the sales team because they aren't held to the same standard as the admin or funeral directors. We have been to management countless times to see what we can do to help them to keep to policy & procedure, the response is "its always been this way". Instead of trying to train the sales team to do things accordingly or having some sort of repercussion for continually not following policy & procedure, we overlook it because "its always been this way". I love what I do specifically but not getting any kind of backup from management makes it hard to not seek employment in a place where EVERY employee is held to the same standard.

column95: Allowing all sales personnel access to incoming leads through calls and walkins.  This week on three different days I called into the location as I was working from home.  Each day I got the answering service between 9:30 and 11:00.  Day one it happened 4 times.  Day two 3 times, Day 3 1 time.  Clearly we have many lost opportunities for revenue because of this.  There is a whole team of people who are acutely qualified to answer calls and book and close appointments who have no access to them.  It has effected income and attitude and has one group have to hunt like crazy to find something to sell,m while the other thrives off of incoming calls and walks and the referrals from them.  Really sad and ultimately bad for the organization.

column120: There was a time when I would have been able to give highly positive Characteristic Statements and Value Statements too about Restland.  However I have watched persons with little to no integrity year after year be allowed to remain with the organization despite being identified and the issues known.  Some of them have been downgraded to lower positions.  But with human nature being what it is, it is clear that did not fix their lack of integrity.  I have been told it is because they can sell.  What does that say about how our organization  feels about the sales process?  I have always excelled in the field and have never had to cheat others to do it.  I would like to think the the company puts integrity first...but that does not appear to be the case.Further, sometimes I think that the management strategies are quite abusive and archaic.  Witholding earnings not because a blue form is not turned in, but because it is not uploaded into CRM is an example.  When you have never been shown how to do it and you therefore go to the Admin., and the Memorial departments and they don't know how to do it either...there appears to be a problem with the training arm of the process.  One of my leaders is exceptional at these things, including integrity and the other not so much.  It is a shame though that it is the producer of the revenue that gets hurt in these types of situations.  I think it is reasonable to conclude when these types of things happen it can hurt motivation to continue to produce.

column95: I see a lot of people on a day shift consistently complaining about things that are minor and they do themselves. We work hard in our shift. However, I openly expressed to every person I work with I am open and willing to speak to them and solve any issues they may have. However, the same people go to management, and when managment does the right thing by saying me that person who is having the issue. And my managers need to sit down face to face, the person avoids the meeting. We have rescheduled this meeting. I don't think we need babysitters and it's silly that co workers cannot solve an issue by speaking to the person about it. We are adults. I see some people pointing fingers at everything but themselves. I don't understand how someone can have that lack of self understanding to see that this is not a solution, no one would be upset with anyone if we spoke honestly and openly about any issues. We are adults, yet, act as children. I don't see accountability in certain people. I have no issue admitting my mistakes. It clarifies and helps everyone fully grasp the situation. I understand we don't wish to lose people but, there must be consequences, EQUALLY, and I'm not unincluding myself.
column96: When I felt like we all got together and buckled down on a large call volume and case load. Day shift stayed and in turn we were able to get people ready for the next day. I don't leave my team regress if they like me or not just because  it's time to go. We have to stop point finders and not looking at ourselfves.

column95: Nurture a culture where people will work until 8-9 pm because they love our company and what we do.    You have people who care about the company, its customers, its image, the employees are devoted to NorthStar's success.  We are falling in a zone like a company that I left... everything is urgent, and must be "completed by the end of business today"  everything has a date attached.  You have people who care, but the pressure we as a company place on our teams with these types of "get it done" "Pump it out" mindsets is hurting the creativity and overall happiness of your people.  You are blessed with people that work hard.  I encourage the leadership to rethink how they push tasks out to the field.  If continued It will erode and destroy the special place NorthStar built.  The company environment in the past created entrepreneurs and  that is not happening with the same frequency.  Nurture a culture where people will work until 8-9 pm because they love our company and what we do, not because they will get in trouble if they don't.

column95: Having an independent care center location manager that is NOT the location manager of another funeral home would have the greatest positive impact. Other locations are often treated poorly, bullied, given the worst choice of pick up times, because the LM's funeral home location is favored over the rest. LM complains about sending attendant help to other locations however, LM doesn't express to HR that the removal technicians from the care center are placed on attendant duty for the LM's funeral location, to take flowers etc etc, and removals are held, halted, or assigned to a third party removal. Most of the time, the third party removal company are assigned to OTHER locations cases, therefore charging those locations for a third party removal and tries to keep the care center removal techs on the LM's funeral home's calls for removal. Issues have arised, and they have been addressed or looked into VERY one-sided by HR and VPs, always favoring the care center.

column95: My experience of Restland under NSMG's culture:  Shifting the focus from profit dollars to profitable company culture needs to happen.    It is so obvious that money is the driving narrative from management-the corporate rhetoric is indifferent to the families who work here, have family resting here, and serving the families that purchase here.  The death care industry should NOT be run with a corporate state of mind especially in today's social media laden world and the specific historical significance Restland has in Dallas and Texas.  There are generations of family here that no longer have faith in us and they have valid complaints about the neglect of our cemetery and integrity within our funeral home operations.  We keep being told NSMG doesn't have the money to fund Restland properly to restore it etc. and that answer is unacceptable. The perceived company indifference only layers on resentment from employees and clients.  Restland needs more help than perhaps NSMG can give it?  We need millions to fix the years of neglect, just look at our sidewalks and how terrible the cemetery looks.  If first impressions are all that matter, ours is an embarrassment to the many wonderful folks that work here and truly want to help.  The public may be punitive at times with how they experience our breakdowns as human beings serving others, BUT they are also very aware that the "company" doesn't care anymore.  We simply do not have enough man power or company investment to restore all the damage from previous ownership and neglect.  Regardless of the P and L statements, this industry has to put people first.  There are so many good folks at Restland who give their all but without the company being willing to put more money into Restland we ultimately suffer the hardship of disappointing folks during the worst time of their life.  This leaves a lasting traumatic impression during what should be an opportunity to help folks grieve well.  How can we do God's work when our hands our tied?  I understand profit matters to sustainability but all you need to do is spend one day here to see the lost faith in our employees and families. Most of us work here and have family resting here.  This place may not be able to be restored to it's old days of glory but that is certainly no reason to give up on Restland.  I feel there needs to be more money spent here than anyone is willing to do because of the rhetoric of profit over people.  It is so obvious our VP of sales could care less about anything other than money and expresses an attitude of self importance rather than helping the team including our sales manager.  Sales mean nothing if the company cannot follow through.  Sparkman Hillcrest may be just as challenging behind the scenes but at least they keep their grounds presentable and "hide" their problems from the public.  Restland is so out of control in the public's perception that "I am sorry" is not enough.  Something big really needs to shift in the focus and narrative of how NSMG perceives success even if it costs them  PROFIT or BONUS.  How do they expect us to sell a $60000 estate when the grounds look awful, you may not get the funeral director you met and worked with on the day of your funeral, and all we can tell folks is "we are sorry and are working on it".  It is my understanding that the Abbey Maus Roof should have been replaced years ago-how did this happen?  It is beautiful and has amazing property still available but it is in a state of decay that is humiliating to Restland.  I don't know what the answer is but I do know it will take making decisions that aren't normal to a corporate mentality of profit only.  I am not saying that NSMG is bad nor are the folks who are at the top-but this lack of connection to the real issue-serving our families-has to stop.  We are losing more families each day to our competitors and they will sadly and gladly tell you a consistent story of why they left our care.  They will generally say: we nickel and dime, our prices no longer reflect our quality of service, our cemetery looks terrible, and they cannot trust us-period.  In an ever changing world with more and more disinformation spread without consequence folks are smarting up and going to spend where they will be treated like people not profit.  My family is buried here and I LOVE my job however I have to pray for Restland and everything I sell.  I pray we can restore and rebuild before we become yet another casualty of corporate greed.

column120: Frank Stewart would turn over in his grave with what this company has been reduced to. If this is the only poor survey, there are several dishonest employees working here, which I guess should appeal to this Diet SCI organization. It was my understanding the founders of Northstar left SCI due to wanting to make a better experience for grieving families, yet the ship is slowly turning away from that star and back from whence it came. Currently and consistently, core issues and correct personnel are NEVER corrected. In fact, often the blame is placed on people who have nothing to do with issue (and cannot defend themselves) and are then forced to take on said issue transferring pressure, heat and communications. Extreme ownership does not apply to all.  Management could not be less interested in their jobs, thinking since they have made it to the 'big chair' they no longer have to put in the work. Management believes only the word of sales and no-one else. I know this because no-one is ever asked their side.  I suppose it is due to the fact the allegedly sales bring the money. Ironically, due in large part to sales, we lose a ton of money with law suits, rush ordering, overnight shipping, refunds,  funerals, plots and merchandise we have to give away. Location is reactive, not proactive. I could go on, need I? Additionally, are these surveys even read, much less taken seriously if submitted by field admin?
